title: For Sale/Trade:  Pioneer Arms/IO Inc Polish Radom PPS43-C 9x19mm / 9mm Luger
location: West Metro, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: This is a redesign of the Polish 1943 submachine gun by Pioneer Arms and IO Inc to fire semi auto only from the closed bolt position.  It a recentl manufacture by Pioneer Arms at the famed Radom Plant in Poland using all authentic Polish made parts and components.  This version is chambered from the factory in the 9x19mm cartirdge.  It features a safety located at the front of the trigger guard, receiver and barrel shroud made from stamped steel, L-shaped fixed rear sight, fixed blade front sight, and a barrel equipped with a simple muzzle brake.  This firearm is legally classified as a pistol by the ATF as the stock is permanently welded in the folded closed position.  The gun will come with 2-9mm specific 30 round curved magazines that have been stored in plastic bags with a thin film of oil since the gun was purchaserd.  This gun has seen limited use as I had intended to turn this into a short barreled rifle, but aquired another 9mm carbine shortly after purchasing it.  I now own several pistol caliber carbines and don't have a need for another in the 9x19mm cartridge.  I do like the platform and still think it has great potential as an SBR, but would instead like to aquire one in the original 7.62x25mm cartridge.  This is more for historical value as well as to be a companion gun for my CZ 52 pistols also in 7.62x25.  This gun is a blast to shoot and will be much cheaper to feed in 9mm if you're just looking for a fun range/recreational gun.  It could also serve as a good home defense gun due to it's high firepower, compact size, and proven service record in  its sub machine gun form.  I've read that the 9mm guns will run fine with standard surplus magazines, which are still relatively cheap and available, but I cannot personally confirm this.  The 9mm magazines have worked well and the gun ran with no issues when originally test fired.  It was wiped down and has basically sat since then so may require cleaning and lubricating but otherwise this gun is practically new!  These seam to have dried up completely on the import market and I can only find them available on the secondary market.  This has begun to drive up prices lately and if you've been thinking about getting one of these now might be the time while prices are still reasonable.
